{{Infobox book | name = History of the Prophets and Kings | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = [[al-Tabari]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = تاريخ الرسل والملوك | orig_lang_code = ar | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = [[Arabic]] | series = | release_number = | subject = History of Islam and the Middle East | genre = | publisher = | publisher2 = | pub_date = 10th century | english_pub_date = | published = | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }} The '''''History of the Prophets and Kings''''' ({{lang-ar|تاريخ الرسل والملوك}} ''Tārīkh al-Rusul wa al-Mulūk''), more commonly known as '''''Tarikh al-Tabari''''' ({{lang|ar|تاريخ الطبري}}) or '''''Tarikh-i Tabari''''' ({{lang-fa|تاریخ طبری}}) is an [[Arabic]]-language historical [[chronicle]] written by the [[Greater Iran|Persian]]<ref>[[Gaston Wiet]], etc, "The Great Medieval Civilizations: cultural and scientific development. Volume 3. The great medieval civilizations. Part 1", Published by Allen and Unwin, 1975. pg 722:In the meantime another author, Tabari, Persian by origin, had been unobtrusively at work on two monumental pieces of writing, a commentary on the Koran ..</ref> historian [[Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari]] (838-923). It begins with [[Creation myth|the Creation]] to 915 AD, and contains detail concerning [[Muslim history|Muslim]] and [[history of the Middle East|Middle Eastern history]]. An ''al-Sila'', appendix<ref>''Autonomous Egypt from Ibn Tulun to Kafur, 868-969'', Thierry Bianquis, '''The Cambridge History of Egypt''', Vol. 1, ed. M. W. Daly, Carl F. Petry, (Cambridge University Press, 1998), 98.</ref> or continuation,<ref>''History and Historians'', Claude Cahen, '''Religion, Learning and Science in the 'Abbasid Period''', 203</ref> was written by Abu Abdullah b. Ahmad b. Ja'far al-Farghani, a Turk student of al-Tabari.<ref>''History and Historians'', Claude Cahen, '''Religion, Learning and Science in the 'Abbasid Period''', ed. M. J. L. Young, J. D. Latham, R. B. Serjeant, (Cambridge University Press, 1990), 203.</ref><ref>[[Ibn Jarir al-Tabari]], ''The History of al-Tabari Vol. 1: General Introduction and From the Creation to the Flood'', transl. Franz Rosenthal, (State University of New York Press, 1989), 7.</ref>
==Editions== <!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:History Al-Tabari.jpg|left|100px]] --> Various editions of the Annals include: * An edition published under the editorship of [[Michael Jan de Goeje|M.J. de Goeje]] in three series comprising thirteen volumes, with two extra volumes containing indices, introduction and glossary (Leiden, 1879–1901). * An edition published under the editorship of [[Muhammad Abu al-Fadl Ibrahim]] (1905-1981) in ten volumes (al-Qahira: Dar al-Ma'arif, 1960-1969.) * A Persian digest of this work, made in 963 by the [[Samanid]] scholar [[Bal'ami|al-Bal'ami]], translated into [[French language|French]] by [[Hermann Zotenberg]] (vols. i.-iv., [[Paris]], 1867–1874). * An English translation in 39 volumes (plus index), published by the [[State University of New York Press]] from 1985 through 2007. Various editors and 29 translators. {{ISBN|978-0-7914-7249-1}} (hc), {{ISBN|978-0-7914-7250-7}} (pb), Author: Tabari (various translators), Publisher: SUNY Press <ref>[http://www.sunypress.edu/details.asp?id=61520 SUNY Press :: History of al-Tabari<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
